stories.text:
Skill set was C++ but also web tech such as React / Angular. Javascript. Current side projects are node/react/flutter.

I worked for myself. So I have no current experience. Ordinary employers seem to see this as red flag. No callbacks.

Are portfolios still a thing or should I go for non-profits and rebuild a network that way? Portfolios got me work back when I was contracting.

How would I transition back in? I'm in 40s.
stories.title: Ask HN: Out of IT for 3 years. How to get back in after working for self?

stories.text:
For work, classes, and general curiosity I've spent time on sites like stack overflow and other stack exchanges. I've definitely spent a ton of time on stack overflow specifically for its efficiency of solving simple questions, but mainly it's my favorite because of the rare answers that go on for paragraphs explaining the intricacies of some rando's question that seem to stand out, at first, as being an unfit length for the question but end up leaving me wondering why this isn't a full blown medium or html/css-only-type-blog post.

Who makes these crazy awesome stack overflow answers? What's their life look like? Are they just another eng in my company, and do I know any?
stories.title: Who are the popular stack overflow?
